Most likely related , but  the same build/compilation of above api spec gives me the following error
```
restapi/operations/app_api.go:275:19: o.context.APIHandlerSwaggerUI undefined (type *middleware.Context has no field or method APIHandlerSwaggerUI)
```

@hhubris @hgedia I've just tried your use case (without the go.mod) and it generates the expected imports.
```
swagger generate server --spec fixture-2362.yaml --target internal --model-package restapi/model

grep 'models"' internal/restapi/operations/*.go
internal/restapi/operations/ping_responses.go:	"github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/fixtures/bugs/2362/internal/restapi/models"

go build ./internal/cmd/foo-bar-server
echo $?
0
```

Still trying to figure out how I can reproduce your issue...

Doing the same with an initialized module, and this still works ok for me.
```
go mod init github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/fixtures/bugs/2362
swagger generate ...

grep 'models"' internal/restapi/operations/*.go
internal/restapi/operations/ping_responses.go:	"github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/fixtures/bugs/2362/internal/restapi/models"

go build ...
echo  $?
0
```

I am using: 
```
go version
go version go1.14.4 linux/amd64
```
swagger command built from source at tag v0.25.0.

I spent quite a bit of time trying to replicate this today, and I finally did.  I'm not sure what the root cause is, but can you try this shell script.  When I run this, I end up with the incorrect import here: 

```
$ head -20 internal/restapi/operations/ping_responses.go
// Code generated by go-swagger; DO NOT EDIT.

package operations

// This file was generated by the swagger tool.
// Editing this file might prove futile when you re-run the swagger generate command

import (
	"net/http"

	"github.com/go-openapi/runtime"

	"github.com/foo/bar/internal/models"
)

// PingOKCode is the HTTP code returned for type PingOK
const PingOKCode int = 200

/*PingOK OK
```

This is the script I used to build.

```
#!/usr/bin/env sh

rm -rf internal/restapi/models
rm -rf internal/restapi/operations

swagger generate server \
  --spec spec/swagger.yaml \
  --target internal \
  --model-package restapi/models \
  --principal models.Principal \
  --exclude-main \
  --name data-updater
```
ok the problem comes from the use of the principal, which I have slightly changed after v0.24.0 (to fix some other issues with it). Let's see in details how it goes.

specifying the principal with a fully qualified package does the job, e.g.:
```
swagger generate server \
  --spec fixture-2362.yaml \
  --target internal \
  --model-package restapi/models \
  --principal github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/fixtures/bugs/2362/internal/restapi/models.Principal \
  --exclude-main \
  --name data-updater
```

The change is due to https://github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/pull/2325
The problem fixed by that one is when the principal is retrieved from some package outside the generated tree.

However, it looks that this fix overlooked the case of the "models" package, which generates a conflicting import.

Your suggested fix does work, and after updating all of the openapi dependencies, the code builds cleanly.

Is this fix backwards compatible?  Specifically if someone on the team rebuilds w/ v0.24.0 will it work?  Or should I revert the change and wait for v0.25.1?

Thanks for your help

There is nothing new to be expected on that >v0.25.0.

Specifically, even though we could make the package guess logic even smarter, this would be an enhancement, not a priority.

I think that specifying the principal with a full package would work in v0.24.0 just as well. I haven't checked, though.

@hhubris reconsidering a bit your use case. I believe it is rather common to do something like this, so the change brought by v0.25.0 about how to specify the package where to find principal is somehow breaking older habits. I'll try to enhance this so we get a smarter package resolution.

@fredbi when the generate server uses the --template=stratoscale flag you get the error that @hgedia mentions.

Also, I know I'm hijacking a bit the topic, but related to the --template=stratoscale flag and #2290 , when you try to use the file type in a response you will get a "csv producer has not yet been implemented"
same here. using --template get the same error

issue.title: principal alias imports bug in v0.25.0
issue.body:
## Problem statement

After upgrading from 0.24.0 to 0.25.0, aliased principal types are now being replaced by the types that they are aliases of. This breaks the generated code because it leads to importing /internal/ packages.

This is the diff in our generated code that resulted from the upgrade:
```
import (
        "net/http"

-       "<redacted>/lib/auth"
        "github.com/go-openapi/runtime/middleware"
+
+       "<redacted>/service/<redacted>/internal/<redacted>/auth"
 )
```

## Swagger specification
hopefully not relevant

## Steps to reproduce

Upgrade from 0.24.0 to 0.25.0.
Command run:
```
go run github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/cmd/swagger generate server --target ./generated --name <redacted> --spec ./<redacted>.yaml --exclude-main -q --principal=auth.<redacted>
```

## Environment
swagger version: 0.25.0
go version: go1.14.4
OS:  linux/amd64
